problem: On Monday, I worked $t-6$ hours and earned $2t-5$ dollars per hour. My friend Andrew worked $2t-8$ hours but only earned $t-5$ dollars an hour. As it turns out, we earned the same amount. What is the value of $t$?
solution:
Since we both earned the same amount, \begin{align*}
(t-6) (2t-5) &= (2t-8)(t-5) \\
\Rightarrow \qquad 2t^2-17t+30 &= 2t^2 - 18t+ 40.
\end{align*}Simplifying gives $t = \boxed{10}$.
model_solution:
Step 1: Write an equation based on the given information.
$(t-6)(2t-5) = (2t-8)(t-5)$
Step 2: Expand the equation.
$2t^{2}-17t+30 = 2t^{2}-18t+40$
Step 3: Subtract $2t^{2}$ from both sides of the equation.
$-17t+30 = -18t+40$
Subtract 30 from both sides of the equation.

$-17t = -18t+10$
Add $18t$ to both sides of the equation.
Add 10 to both sides of the equation.

$-17t + 18t = 10$
$-t = 10$
Divide both sides of the equation by -1.

$-t = 10$

$ t = -10$
Divide both sides of the equation by -1.

$ t = -10$
Step 4: Divide both sides of the equation by -1.

$ t = -10$
Check if $t=-10$ satisfies the original equation.

$(-10-6)(2(-10)-5) \stackrel{?}{=} (2(-10)-8)((-10)-5)$
